Rohit Satyam*

This vignette outlines an analysis workflow for a DNA methylation dataset in blood monocytes from severe COVID-19 patients. The data is obtained from Godoy-Tena et al 2022 paper. Most of the code here is borrowed from methylationArrayAnalysis vignette here

  • The minfi, IlluminaHumanMethylation450kanno.ilmn12.hg19, IlluminaHumanMethylation450kmanifest, missMethyl, minfiData, and DMRcate packages are specific to methylation analysis, while RColorBrewer and Gviz are used for visualization.
  • We use limma to test for differential methylation, and matrixStats and stringr provide functions essential to the workflow.
  • The IlluminaHumanMethylation450kmanifest package offers the Illumina manifest as an R object, which can be easily loaded into the environment.
  • This manifest contains all annotation information for each CpG probe on the 450k array, which is helpful for determining the genomic context of differentially methylated probes.

0.3 Quality Control

Now, we calculate detection p-values, which provide an indication of signal quality. A detection p-value is generated for each CpG in every sample. Minfi calculates these p-values by comparing the total signal (M + U) M= methylated and U= unmethylated for each probe to the background signal, estimated from negative control probes. Very small p-values suggest a reliable signal, while larger p-values (e.g., >0.01) typically indicate poor signal quality.

Plotting the mean detection p-value for each sample helps us evaluate the overall quality of the samples in terms of signal reliability. Samples with many failed probes tend to have higher mean detection p-values.

# calculate the detection p-values
detP <- detectionP(rgSet, type = "m+u")

0.4 Normalization and data exploration

We’ll use the preprocessQuantile method on our data. This function applies a stratified quantile normalization procedure to the methylated and unmethylated signal intensities separately, while accounting for different probe types. The M and U intensity data are then converted into M-values and beta values, along with their associated genomic coordinates.

# normalize the data; this results in a GenomicRatioSet object
mSetSq <- preprocessQuantile(rgSet) 

# create a MethylSet object from the raw data for plotting
mSetRaw <- preprocessRaw(rgSet)

# visualise what the data looks like before and after normalization
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
densityPlot(rgSet, sampGroups=targets$Sample_Group,main="Raw", legend=FALSE)
legend("top", legend = levels(factor(targets$Sample_Group)), 
       text.col=brewer.pal(8,"Dark2"))
densityPlot(getBeta(mSetSq), sampGroups=targets$Sample_Group,
            main="Normalized", legend=FALSE)
legend("top", legend = levels(factor(targets$Sample_Group)), 
       text.col=brewer.pal(8,"Dark2"))

Now let’s make Multi-dimensional scaling (MDS) plots, based on principal components analysis which are exploratory plots. The plots below reveal similarities and differences between samples, with similar samples clustering together and dissimilar samples appearing farther apart. The first dimension (principal component 1) captures the most significant source of variation, while subsequent dimensions capture decreasing sources of variation.

# MDS plots to look at largest sources of variation


plotMDS(getM(mSetSq), top=1000, gene.selection="common", labels = NULL,
        col=pal[factor(targets$Sample_Group)], cex = 0.5)
legend("top", legend=levels(factor(targets$Sample_Group)), text.col=pal,
       bg="white", cex=0.7)

0.5 Filtering

Probes with poor performance are typically removed before conducting differential methylation analysis. Since these probes yield unreliable signals, eliminating them reduces the number of statistical tests, thereby lowering the multiple testing penalty. We exclude probes that have failed in one or more samples based on detection p-values, and also filter out probes located at SNPs and on sex chromosomes.

# ensure probes are in the same order in the mSetSq and detP objects
detP <- detP[match(featureNames(mSetSq),rownames(detP)),] 

# remove any probes that have failed in one or more samples
keep <- rowSums(detP < 0.01) == ncol(mSetSq) 
table(keep)

0.6 Probe-wise differential methylation analysis

The biological question of interest for this particular dataset is to discover differentially methylated probes between the covid and healthy samples.

# calculate M-values for statistical analysis
mVals <- getM(mSetSqFlt)

bVals <- getBeta(mSetSqFlt)

#Plotting m and b values
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
densityPlot(bVals, sampGroups=targets$Sample_Group, main="Beta values", 
            legend=FALSE, xlab="Beta values")
legend("top", legend = levels(factor(targets$Sample_Group)), 
       text.col=brewer.pal(8,"Dark2"))
densityPlot(mVals, sampGroups=targets$Sample_Group, main="M-values", 
            legend=FALSE, xlab="M values")
legend("topleft", legend = levels(factor(targets$Sample_Group)), 
       text.col=brewer.pal(8,"Dark2"))

cellType <- factor(targets$Sample_Group, levels = c('Healthy', 'COVID19'))

# create a design matrix
design <- model.matrix(~ 0 + cellType, data = targets)
colnames(design) <- gsub("cellType", "", colnames(design))

# create a contrast matrix for specific comparisons
contMatrix <- makeContrasts(COVID19-Healthy,
                            levels=design)
# linear model
fit <- lmFit(mVals, design)

# fit the contrasts
fit2 <- contrasts.fit(fit, contMatrix)
fit2 <- eBayes(fit2)


# get the table of results for the first contrast (COVID19 - Healthy)
annSub <- annEPIC[match(rownames(mVals),annEPIC$Name),
                      c(1:4,12:19,24:ncol(annEPIC))]
# DMP results
DMPs <- topTable(fit2, num=Inf, coef=1, genelist=annSub)
write.table(DMPs, file="DMPs.csv", sep=",", row.names=FALSE)

# plot the top 4 most significantly differentially methylated CpGs 
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
sapply(rownames(DMPs)[1:4], function(cpg){
  plotCpg(bVals, cpg=cpg, pheno=targets$Sample_Group, ylab = "Beta values")
})

0.7 Differential methylation analysis of regions

We are interested in knowing whether several proximal CpGs are concordantly differentially methylated, that is, we want to identify differentially methylated regions. The plot below shows the location of the DMR in the genome, the position of any genes that are nearby, the base pair positions of the CpG probes, the methylation levels of the individual samples as a heatmap and the mean methylation levels for the various sample groups in the experiment. This plot shows one of the DMRs identified by the DMRcate analysis.

myAnnotation <- cpg.annotate(object = mVals, datatype = "array", what = "M", 
                             analysis.type = "differential", design = design, 
                             contrasts = TRUE, cont.matrix = contMatrix, 
                             coef = "COVID19 - Healthy", arraytype = "EPICv1")

DMRs <- dmrcate(myAnnotation, lambda=1000, C=2)
results.ranges <- extractRanges(DMRs)

0.8 Differential variability

detP <- detectionP(rgSet, type = "m+u")
mSetSq <- preprocessQuantile(rgSet)


targets$Sex <- getSex(mSetSq)$predictedSex
detP <- detP[match(featureNames(mSetSq),rownames(detP)),]

keep <- rowSums(detP < 0.01) == ncol(detP) 
mSetSqFlt <- mSetSq[keep,]
mSetSqFlt <- dropLociWithSnps(mSetSqFlt, snps = c("CpG", "SBE"))

plotMDS(getM(mSetSqFlt), top=1000, gene.selection="common", 
        col=pal[factor(targets$Sample_Group)], labels=targets$Sex, 
        main="With Sex CHR Probes")

# get M-values for analysis
mVals <- getM(mSetSqFlt)

design <- model.matrix(~factor(targets$Sample_Group)) 
fitvar <- varFit(mVals, design = design, coef = c(1,2))

# Summary of differential variability
summary(decideTests(fitvar))

0.9 Inference

Differential Methylation Pattern analysis revealed: - Significant methylation differences at sites like cg19938920 and cg01995927, which are located in genes involved in immune modulation. - These epigenetic changes may impact gene expression, potentially contributing to the abnormal immune responses observed in severe COVID-19 patients by affecting monocyte function and increasing inflammation.

Gene Ontology Testing showed: - Significant enrichment in pathways such as “immune response” and “leukocyte activation.” - This suggests that epigenetic modifications in severe COVID-19 may prime leukocytes toward a hyperactivated state, potentially exacerbating inflammation and tissue damage.

Differential Variability in Methylation: - The results indicated higher methylation variability at certain CpGs in COVID-19 patients, like cg20648333 and cg23595055, indicating a dynamic epigenetic response to infection. - This variability could affect gene regulation and influence how monocytes respond to the disease, potentially contributing to the severity of infection.

Potential Impact on Monocyte Differentiation: - Observed methylation changes could influence monocyte differentiation, potentially skewing development towards more inflammatory subtypes or those less capable of resolving inflammation. - This shift might play a significant role in the pathology of severe COVID-19 by affecting the immune system’s response to the virus.
